Correlation

attach(fuel)
cor(Fuel, Tax)
## [1] -0.4512803

** Pearson’s Correlation** - Oldest form of correlation and most tied to linear regression, not necessarily the most intuitive. If type of correlation is unspecified, it’s pearson’s correlation.

Correlation is between -1 and 1.

What correlation doesn’t explain

cor(x,y3)
## [1] 7.080628e-20
plot(x,y3)
abline(lm(y3~x), col="blue", lwd=2)

Pearson’s Correlation only explains when variables are related by a line. Thus it gives us 0 for the plot of x, y3 above. Even though we know they are perfectly related.

What correlation does not measure: - whether variables are realted - whether a line is appropriate - “bang for buck” - whether model is useful – coefficients are always right for the mdoel that they are in, so their meaning and implications highly depend on the model.

$ Y= {0} +{1}Tax + _{2}License +$ \(\epsilon ~ N(0, \sigma^2)\)

pick \(\hat\beta_{0}, \hat\beta_{1}, \hat\beta_{2}\) to minimize –> Now just solving three linear equations with three unknowns.

General form of the linear model $ Y= {0} + {1}X_{1} + {2}X{2} + … + {k}X{k} + $ where $ ~ N(0, ^2)$
